To create a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 that responds to a `/ban` slash command, follow these steps:

1. First, install the Discord.js library if you haven't already:
```bash
npm install discord.js
```

2. Create a new file, let's call it `bot.js`, and use the following code:

```javascript
const { Client, GatewayIntentBits, SlashCommandBuilder } = require('discord.js');
const { TOKEN } = require('./config.json'); // Make sure to create a config.json file with your bot token

// Initialize the client
const client = new Client({ intents: [GatewayIntentBits.Guilds, GatewayIntentBits.GuildMembers, GatewayIntentBits.GuildModeration] });

// Command setup
client.on('ready', () => {
    console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}`);

    // Register the ban command globally
    client.application.commands.register(new SlashCommandBuilder()
        .setName('ban')
        .setDescription('Bans a member from the server.')
        .addUserOption(option => option
            .setName('target')
            .setDescription('The member to ban.')
            .setRequired(true))
        .addStringOption(option => option
            .setName('reason')
            .setDescription('The reason for the ban.')
            .setRequired(false)));
});

// Command handler
client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
    if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

    if (interaction.commandName === 'ban') {
        if (!interaction.member.permissions.has('BAN_MEMBERS')) {
            return interaction.reply({ content: 'You do not have the permission to ban members.', ephemeral: true });
        }

        const target = interaction.options.getUser('target');
        const reason = interaction.options.getString('reason') || 'No reason provided';

        try {
            await interaction.guild.members.ban(target, { reason });
            await interaction.reply(`Successfully banned ${target.tag} for: ${reason}`);
        } catch (error) {
            console.error(error);
            await interaction.reply('There was an error trying to ban that member.');
        }
    }
});

// Run the bot
client.login(TOKEN);
```

3. Create a `config.json` file in the same directory as `bot.js` and add your bot token:
```json
{
    "TOKEN": "your-bot-token-here"
}
```
Replace "your-bot-token-here" with your actual bot token, which you can get from the Discord Developer Portal.

4. Finally, run your bot with:
```bash
node bot.js
```

Make sure to invite your bot to your server with the necessary permissions, and you'll be able to use the `/ban` command. Remember that the bot will need the `Ban Members` permission, and you should enable the `Application Commands` feature in the Discord Developer Portal for your bot.

To create a C++ function that converts Markdown to HTML, you can use a library like `markdown-cpp` or write your own simple parser for basic Markdown features. I'll provide a basic example of how you could implement a simple Markdown to HTML converter function, focusing on a few core features like headers, emphasis, links, and lists. Keep in mind, this is a very simplified version and doesn't cover the full Markdown specification.

First, let's assume you don't want to use an external library and want to create a basic function yourself:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdown_to_html(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html;
    std::regex rules{
        R"!(\#+)\s*(.*)"i,   // Headers
        R"!(\*\*|__)(.*?)(\*\*|__)!"s, // Bold
        R"!(\*|_)(.*?)(\*|_)!"s,      // Italic
        R"!(\[(.*)\]\((.*)\))!"s,     // Links
        R"!(\n\s*-\s*(.*))!"s        // Unordered lists
    };
    std::string replacement{
        R"!(<h\1>\2</h\1>)!"s,
        R"!(<strong>\2</strong>)!"s,
        R"!(<em>\2</em>)!"s,
        R"!(<a href="\2">\1</a>)!"s,
        R"!(<li>\2</li>)!"s
    };

    std::string temp_markdown = markdown;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < rules.size(); ++i) {
        temp_markdown = std::regex_replace(temp_markdown, rules[i], replacement[i]);
    }

    // Convert line breaks to <br> tags, except for those inside <pre>...</pre>
    std::regex line_breaks(R"!(\n)(?!(?:[^<]|<[^>]*)>)(?!<\/pre>)!s");
    html = std::regex_replace(temp_markdown, line_breaks, "<br>");

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Hello\n\nThis is **bold** and *italic*. [Visit StackOverflow](https://stackoverflow.com).\n\n- Item 1\n- Item 2";
    std::string html = markdown_to_html(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

This code provides a basic conversion for headers, bold, italic, links, and unordered lists. It also adds `<br>` for line breaks not inside `<pre>` tags. It's important to note that this is a very simplified implementation and doesn't handle all Markdown features, edge cases, or complex formatting. For a complete and robust solution, using an existing library would be recommended.

